Author: CrispStrobe <cze+github@mailbox.org>
Date:   Wed Apr 29 08:25:28 2026 +0200

    refactor(tools): factor per-iteration capture + audio diff into reusable helpers
    
    After the issue #39 vibevoice work, two patterns are worth lifting out
    so future TTS diff harnesses (qwen3-tts AR, future TTS backends) don't
    re-implement them.
    
    `tools/reference_backends/_iter_capture.py` is the AR-sampler companion
    to `_hooks.py`. `_hooks.py` covers static `nn.Module.forward` hooks (one
    tensor per stage); `_iter_capture` covers monkey-patched sampler entry
    points where state is only visible inside an internal loop:
    
      - VibeVoice: `sample_speech_tokens` runs DPM-Solver++ iterations;
        pos/neg cond, init noise, v_cfg @ step 0, final latent are visible
        only inside.
      - Qwen3-TTS-talker: `generate()` runs greedy AR; per-step talker
        logits / codec head outputs are similarly invisible to a single
        forward_hook.
    
    API mirrors `_hooks.py`:
      - append(captured, stage, tensor)        — one frame
      - patch_method(obj, name, wrap)          — returns restore() closure
      - drop_handles(handles)                  — handles both forward_hook
                                                 handles AND restore()
                                                 closures
      - dump_perframe_dir(captured, out_dir)   — writes
                                                 `perframe_<stage>_f<NNN>.bin`
                                                 + `noise.bin` (if "noise"
                                                 present in captured)
    
    `tools/run_official_vibevoice.py` now uses these helpers (was ad-hoc
    dict + manual hook + inline dump loop).
    
    `tools/_audio_diff.py` is the second helper, for sample-wise WAV
    comparison after the latent stage matches:
    
      - load_wav_mono(path)          → (float64 [-1, 1], sr)
      - cos_at_zero_shift(a, b)
      - cos_at_xcorr_peak(a, b, …)   — for trims / causal-padding offsets
      - spectral_band_powers / hf_floor / summary_row / format_table
      - cos_report(a_path, b_path)
    
    Validated on the issue #39 dumps — `cos_report` reproduces the
    0.9991-at-xcorr-peak / 322 ms shift result from the original
    debugging session.
    
